# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: spdlog-cpp-lib
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/c] C++ was designed with systems programming and embedded, resource-constrained software and large systems in mind, with performance, efficiency, and flexibility of use as its design highlights.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/c] C++ is standardized by the International Organization for Standardization (ISO), with the latest standard version ratified and published by ISO in October 2024 as *ISO/IEC 14882:2024* (informally known as C++23).
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/c] The C++ programming language was initially standardized in 1998 as *ISO/IEC 14882:1998*, which was then amended by the C++03, C++11, C++14, C++17, and C++20 standards.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/c] The next C++23 standard superseded these with new features and an enlarged standard library.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/c] Before the initial standardization in 1998, C++ was developed by Stroustrup at Bell Labs since 1979 as an extension of the C language; he wanted an efficient and flexible language similar to C that also provided high-level features for program organization.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/c] Since 2012, C++ has been on a three-year release schedule with C++29 as the next planned standard.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/c] In 1979, Bjarne Stroustrup, a Danish computer scientist, began work on "C with Classes", the predecessor to C++.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/c] The motivation for creating a new language originated from Stroustrup's experience in programming for his PhD thesis.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/c] Stroustrup found that Simula had features that were very helpful for large software development, but the language was too slow for practical use, while BCPL was fast but too low-level to be suitable for large software development.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/c] When Stroustrup started working in AT&T Bell Labs, he had the problem of analyzing the UNIX kernel with respect to distributed computing.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/c] Remembering his PhD experience, Stroustrup set out to enhance the C language with Simula-like features.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/c] C was chosen because it was general-purpose, fast, portable, and widely used.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/c] In addition to C and Simula's influences, other languages influenced this new language, including ALGOL 68, Ada, CLU, and ML.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/c] Initially, Stroustrup's "C with Classes" added features to the C compiler, Cpre, including classes, derived classes, strong typing, inlining, and default arguments.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/c] In 1982, Stroustrup began designing a cleaned-up and extended successor to C with Classes, using traditional compiler technology.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/c] The language was briefly called C84 before the name C++ was adopted; the name was suggested by Rick Mascitti and refers to C's `++` increment operator.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/c] The resulting language included virtual functions, function and operator overloading, references, `const`, improved type checking, user-controlled free-store memory allocation (`new`/`delete`), and BCPL-style single-line `//` comments.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/c] Stroustrup also designed and implemented Cfront, the C++ compiler front end, between spring 1982 and summer 1983.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/c] In 1984, Stroustrup implemented the first stream input/output library.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/c] The idea of providing an output operator rather than a named output function was suggested by Doug McIlroy (who had previously suggested Unix pipes).
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/c] In 1985, the first edition of *The C++ Programming Language* was released, which became the definitive reference for the language, as there was not yet an official standard.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/c] The first commercial implementation of C++ was released in October of the same year.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/c] In 1989, C++ 2.0 was released, followed by the updated second edition of *The C++ Programming Language* in 1991.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/c] New features in 2.0 included multiple inheritance, abstract classes, static member functions, const member functions, and protected members.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/c] In 1990, *The Annotated C++ Reference Manual* was published.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/c] This work became the basis for the future standard.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/c] Later feature additions included templates, exceptions, namespaces, new casts, and a Boolean type.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/c] In 1998, C++98 was released, standardizing the language, and a minor update (C++03) was released in 2003.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/c] After C++98, C++ evolved relatively slowly until, in 2011, the C++11 standard was released, adding numerous new features, enlarging the standard library further, and providing more facilities to C++ programmers.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/c] After a minor C++14 update released in December 2014, various new additions were introduced in C++17.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/c] After becoming finalized in February 2020, a draft of the C++20 standard was approved on 4 September 2020, and officially published on 15 December 2020.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/c] On January 3, 2018, Stroustrup was announced as the 2018 winner of the Charles Stark Draper Prize for Engineering, "for conceptualizing and developing the C++ programming language".
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/c] In December 2022, C++ ranked third on the TIOBE index, surpassing Java for the first time in the history of the index.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/c] As of November 2024, the language ranks second after Python, with Java being in third.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/c] In March 2025, Stroustrup issued a call for the language community to defend it.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/c] Since the language allows manual memory management, bugs that represent security risks such as buffer overflow may be introduced in programs when inadvertently misused by the programmer.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/c] According to Stroustrup, "the name signifies the evolutionary nature of the changes from C." This name is credited to Rick Mascitti (mid-1983) and was first used in December 1983.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/c] When Mascitti was questioned informally in 1992 about the naming, he indicated that it was given in a tongue-in-cheek spirit.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/c] The name comes from C's `++` operator (which increments the value of a variable) and a common naming convention of using "+" to indicate an enhanced computer program.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/c] During C++'s development period, the language had been referred to as "new C" and "C with Classes" before acquiring its final name.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/c] C++ is standardized by an ISO working group known as JTC1/SC22/WG21.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/c] The working group holds three week-long meetings each year.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/c] So far, it has published seven revisions of the C++ standard and is currently working on the next revision, C++26.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/c] In 1998, the ISO working group standardized C++ for the first time as *ISO/IEC 14882:1998*, which is informally known as *C++98*.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/c] In 2003, it published a new version of the C++ standard called *ISO/IEC 14882:2003*, which fixed problems identified in C++98.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/c] The next major revision of the standard was informally referred to as "C++0x", but it was not released until 2011.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/c] C++11 (14882:2011) included many additions to both the core language and the standard library.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/c] In 2014, C++14 (also known as C++1y) was released as a small extension to C++11, featuring mainly bug fixes and small improvements.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/c] The Draft International Standard ballot procedures completed in mid-August 2014.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/c] After C++14, a major revision C++17, informally known as C++1z, was completed by the ISO C++ committee in mid July 2017 and was approved and published in December 2017.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/c] More technical specifications are in development and pending approval.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/c] The C++ language has two main components: a direct mapping of hardware features provided primarily by the C subset, and zero-overhead abstractions based on those mappings.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/c] Stroustrup describes C++ as "a light-weight abstraction programming language [designed] for building and using efficient and elegant abstractions"; and "offering both hardware access and abstraction is the basis of C++.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/c] A hello world program that conforms to the C standard is also a valid C++ hello world program.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/c] The C++ standard specifies both the core language and the standard library.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/c] The library clauses describe the contents of the library, how a well-formed C++ program uses it, and the requirements placed on conforming implementations.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/c] The standard library is organized into areas such as language support, diagnostics, memory management, metaprogramming, general utilities, containers, iterators, ranges, algorithms, strings, text processing, numerics, time, input/output, and concurrency support.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/c] It also provides the facilities of the C standard library through C++ headers such as `<cstdio>` and `<cstdlib>`; except for names defined as macros in C, these declarations are placed in namespace `std`.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/c] Library facilities are traditionally made available by including standard headers, for example `#include <vector>`.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/c] Since C++20, importable standard library headers may also be imported as header units.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/c] C++23 added the named standard library modules `std` and `std.compat`: `std` exports declarations in namespace `std`, while `std.compat` also exports corresponding global namespace declarations for C library facilities.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/c] A major influence on the standard library was the Standard Template Library (STL), a generic programming library proposed to the C++ standards committee by Alexander Stepanov and Meng Lee in 1994.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/c] Its model of containers, iterators, and generic algorithms became part of the Standard C++ Library, although the standard library also includes many other facilities, such as input/output, localization, diagnostics, and the C library subset.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/c] The main aim is to efficiently and consistently write type and resource safe C++.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/c] Despite this, the guidelines are not endorsed by the ISO C++ standards committee and do not represent the consensus of the committee.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/c] The Core Guidelines were announced in the opening keynote at CPPCon 2015.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/c] The Guidelines are accompanied by the Guideline Support Library (GSL), a header-only library of types and functions to implement the Core Guidelines and static checker tools for enforcing Guideline rules.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/c] One of the largest implementations of this is Microsoft's implementation.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/c] Many of the existing features in the GSL have been later integrated into the language, such as `std::byte`, smart pointers, and `std::span`.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/c] To give compiler vendors greater freedom, the C++ standards committee decided not to dictate the implementation of name mangling, exception handling, and other implementation-specific features.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/c] The downside of this decision is that object code produced by different compilers is expected to be incompatible.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/c] There are, however, attempts to standardize compilers for particular machines or operating systems.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/c] For example, the Itanium C++ ABI is processor-independent (despite its name) and is implemented by GCC and Clang.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/c] C++ is often considered to be a superset of C but this is not strictly true.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/c] Most C code can easily be made to compile correctly in C++ but there are a few differences that cause some valid C code to be invalid or behave differently in C++.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/c] For example, C allows implicit conversion from `void*` to other pointer types but C++ does not (for type safety reasons).
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/c] Also, C++ defines many new keywords, such as `new` and `class`, which may be used as identifiers (for example, variable names) in a C program.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/c] Some incompatibilities have been removed by the 1999 revision of the C standard (C99), which now supports C++ features such as line comments (`//`) and declarations mixed with code.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/c] Some of the C99-introduced features were included in the subsequent version of the C++ standard, C++11 (out of those which were not redundant).
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/c] However, the C++11 standard introduces new incompatibilities, such as disallowing assignment of a string literal to a character pointer, which remains valid C.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/c] To intermix C and C++ code, any function declaration or definition that is to be called from/used both in C and C++ must be declared with C linkage by placing it within an `extern "C" {/*...*/}` block.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/c] Such a function may not rely on features depending on name mangling (i.e., function overloading).
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/c] Programs developed in C or C++ often utilize inline assembly to take advantage of its low-level functionalities, greater speed, and enhanced control compared to high-level programming languages when optimizing for performance is essential.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/c] C++ provides support for embedding assembly language using asm declarations, but the compatibility of inline assembly varies significantly between compilers and architectures.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/c] Unlike high-level language features such as Python or Java, assembly code is highly dependent on the underlying processor and compiler implementation.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/c] Different C++ compilers implement inline assembly in distinct ways.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/c] C++ provides two primary methods of integrating ASM code: standalone assembly files, where assembly code is written separately and linked with C++ code.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/c] And inline assembly, where assembly code is embedded within C++ code using compiler-specific extensions.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/data-logger] A **data logger** (also **datalogger** or **data recorder**) is an electronic device that records data over time or about location either with a built-in instrument or sensor or via external instruments and sensors.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/data-logger] Increasingly, but not entirely, they are based on a digital processor (or computer), and called digital data loggers (DDL).
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/data-logger] They generally are small, battery-powered, portable, and equipped with a microprocessor, internal memory for data storage, and sensors.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/data-logger] Some data loggers interface with a personal computer and use software to activate the data logger and view and analyze the collected data, while others have a local interface device (keypad, LCD) and can be used as a stand-alone device.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/data-logger] Data loggers vary from general-purpose devices for various measurement applications to very specific devices for measuring in one environment or application type only.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/data-logger] While it is common for general-purpose types to be programmable, many remain static machines with only a limited number or no changeable parameters.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/data-logger] Electronic data loggers have replaced chart recorders in many applications.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/data-logger] One primary benefit of using data loggers is their ability to automatically collect data on a 24-hour basis.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/data-logger] Upon activation, data loggers are typically deployed and left unattended to measure and record information for the duration of the monitoring period.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/data-logger] This allows for a comprehensive, accurate picture of the environmental conditions being monitored, such as air temperature and relative humidity.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/data-logger] The cost of data loggers has been declining over the years as technology improves and costs are reduced.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/data-logger] Simple single-channel data loggers can cost as little as $25, while more complicated loggers may cost hundreds or thousands of dollars.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/data-logger] Standardization of protocols and data formats has been a problem but is now growing in the industry and XML, JSON, and YAML are increasingly being adopted for data exchange.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/data-logger] The development of the Semantic Web and the Internet of Things is likely to accelerate this present trend.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/data-logger] Several protocols have been standardized including a smart protocol, SDI-12, that allows some instrumentation to be connected to a variety of data loggers.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/data-logger] The use of this standard has not gained much acceptance outside the environmental industry.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/data-logger] SDI-12 also supports multi-drop instruments.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/data-logger] Some data logging companies support the MODBUS standard.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/data-logger] This has been used traditionally in the industrial control area, and many industrial instruments support this communication standard.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/data-logger] Another multi-drop protocol that is now starting to become more widely used is based upon CAN-Bus (ISO 11898).
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/data-logger] Some data loggers use a flexible scripting environment to adapt to various non-standard protocols.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/data-logger] The terms data logging and data acquisition are often used interchangeably.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/data-logger] However, in a historical context, they are quite different.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/data-logger] A data logger is a data acquisition system, but a data acquisition system is not necessarily a data logger.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/data-logger] Data Loggers are changing more rapidly now than ever before.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/data-logger] The original model of a stand-alone data logger is changed to one of a device that collects data but also has access to wireless communications for alarming of events, automatic reporting of data, and remote control.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/data-logger] Data loggers are beginning to serve web pages for current readings, e-mail their alarms, and FTP their daily results into databases or direct to the users.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/data-logger] Very recently, there is a trend to move away from proprietary products with commercial software to open-source software and hardware devices.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/log-file] In computing, **logging** is the act of keeping a log of events that occur in a computer system, such as problems, errors or broad information on current operations.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/log-file] These events may occur in the operating system or in other software.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/log-file] A message or *log entry* is recorded for each such event.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/log-file] These log messages can then be used to monitor and understand the operation of the system, to debug problems, or during an audit.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/log-file] Logging is particularly important in multi-user software, to have a central overview of the operation of the system.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/log-file] In the simplest case, messages are written to a file, called a *log file*.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/log-file] Alternatively, the messages may be written to a dedicated logging system or to a log management software, where it is stored in a database or on a different computer system.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/log-file] Specifically, a *transaction log* is a log of the communications between a system and the users of that system, or a data collection method that automatically captures the type, content, or time of transactions made by a person from a terminal with that system.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/log-file] For Web searching, a transaction log is an electronic record of interactions that have occurred during a searching episode between a Web search engine and users searching for information on that Web search engine.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/log-file] Many operating systems, software frameworks and programs include a logging system.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/log-file] A widely used logging standard is Syslog, defined in IETF RFC 5424.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/log-file] The Syslog standard enables a dedicated, standardized subsystem to generate, filter, record, and analyze log messages.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/log-file] This relieves software developers of having to design and code their ad hoc logging systems.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/log-file] It can also be useful to combine log file entries from multiple sources.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/log-file] It is a different combination that may yield between with related events on different servers.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/log-file] Other solutions employ network-wide querying and reporting.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/log-file] Most database systems maintain some kind of *transaction log*, which are not mainly intended as an audit trail for later analysis, and are not intended to be human-readable.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/log-file] These logs record changes to the stored data to allow the database to recover from crashes or other data errors and maintain the stored data in a consistent state.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/log-file] Thus, database systems usually have both general event logs and transaction logs.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/log-file] The use of data stored in transaction logs of Web search engines, Intranets, and websites can provide valuable insight into understanding the information-searching process of online searchers.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/log-file] This understanding can enlighten information system design, interface development, and devising the information architecture for content collections.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/log-file] Message logs are almost universally plain text files, but IM and VoIP clients (which support textual chat, e.g.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/log-file] Skype) might save them in HTML files or in a custom format to ease reading or enable encryption.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/log-file] Instant messaging and VoIP clients often offer the chance to store encrypted logs to enhance the user's privacy.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/log-file] These logs require a password to be decrypted and viewed, and they are often handled by their respective writing application.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/log-file] Some privacy focused messaging services, such as Signal, record minimal logs about users, limiting their information to connection times.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/log-file] A *server log* is a log file (or several files) automatically created and maintained by a server consisting of a list of activities it performed.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/log-file] A typical example is a web server log which maintains a history of page requests.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/log-file] The W3C maintains a standard format (the Common Log Format) for web server log files, but other proprietary formats exist.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/log-file] Some servers can log information to computer readable formats (such as JSON) versus the human readable standard.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/log-file] More recent entries are typically appended to the end of the file.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/log-file] Information about the request, including client IP address, request date/time, page requested, HTTP code, bytes served, user agent, and referrer are typically added.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/log-file] This data can be combined into a single file, or separated into distinct logs, such as an access log, error log, or referrer log.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/log-file] However, server logs typically do not collect user-specific information.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/log-file] These files are usually not accessible to general Internet users, only to the webmaster or other administrative person of an Internet service.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/log-file] A statistical analysis of the server log may be used to examine traffic patterns by time of day, day of week, referrer, or user agent.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/log-file] Efficient web site administration, adequate hosting resources and the fine tuning of sales efforts can be aided by analysis of the web server logs.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/structured-data] A **data model** is an abstract model that organizes elements of data and standardizes how they relate to one another and to the properties of real-world entities.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/structured-data] For instance, a data model may specify that the data element representing a car be composed of a number of other elements which, in turn, represent the color and size of the car and define its owner.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/structured-data] The corresponding professional activity is called generally *data modeling* or, more specifically, *database design*.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/structured-data] Data models are typically specified by a data expert, data specialist, data scientist, data librarian, or a data scholar.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/structured-data] A data modeling language and notation are often represented in graphical form as diagrams.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/structured-data] A data model can sometimes be referred to as a data structure, especially in the context of programming languages.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/structured-data] Data models are often complemented by function models, especially in the context of enterprise models.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/structured-data] A data model explicitly determines the *structure of data*; conversely, **structured data** is data organized according to an explicit data model or data structure.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/structured-data] Structured data is in contrast to *unstructured data* and *semi-structured data*.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/structured-data] The term ***data model*** can refer to two distinct but closely related concepts.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/structured-data] Sometimes it refers to an abstract formalization of the objects and relationships found in a particular application domain: for example the customers, products, and orders found in a manufacturing organization.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/structured-data] At other times it refers to the set of concepts used in defining such formalizations: for example concepts such as entities, attributes, relations, or tables.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/structured-data] So the "data model" of a banking application may be defined using the entity–relationship "data model".
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/structured-data] This article uses the term in both senses.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/structured-data] Managing large quantities of structured and unstructured data is a primary function of information systems.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/structured-data] Data models describe the structure, manipulation, and integrity aspects of the data stored in data management systems such as relational databases.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/structured-data] They may also describe data with a looser structure, such as word processing documents, email messages, pictures, digital audio, and video: XDM, for example, provides a data model for XML documents.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/structured-data] The main aim of data models is to support the development of information systems by providing the definition and format of data.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/structured-data] According to West and Fowler (1999) "if this is done consistently across systems then compatibility of data can be achieved.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/structured-data] If the same data structures are used to store and access data then different applications can share data.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/structured-data] The results of this are indicated above.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/structured-data] However, systems and interfaces often cost more than they should, to build, operate, and maintain.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/structured-data] They may also constrain the business rather than support it.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/structured-data] A major cause is that the quality of the data models implemented in systems and interfaces is poor".
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/structured-data] The reason for these problems is a lack of standards that will ensure that data models will both meet business needs and be consistent.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/structured-data] A data model explicitly determines the structure of data.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/structured-data] Typical applications of data models include database models, design of information systems, and enabling exchange of data.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/structured-data] Logical data model: describes the semantics, as represented by a particular data manipulation technology.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/structured-data] This consists of descriptions of tables and columns, object oriented classes, and XML tags, among other things.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/structured-data] Physical data model: describes the physical means by which data are stored.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/structured-data] This is concerned with partitions, CPUs, tablespaces, and the like.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/structured-data] The significance of this approach, according to ANSI, is that it allows the three perspectives to be relatively independent of each other.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/structured-data] Storage technology can change without affecting either the logical or the conceptual model.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/structured-data] The table/column structure can change without (necessarily) affecting the conceptual model.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/structured-data] In each case, of course, the structures must remain consistent with the other model.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/structured-data] The table/column structure may be different from a direct translation of the entity classes and attributes, but it must ultimately carry out the objectives of the conceptual entity class structure.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/structured-data] Early phases of many software development projects emphasize the design of a conceptual data model.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/structured-data] Such a design can be detailed into a logical data model.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/structured-data] In later stages, this model may be translated into physical data model.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/structured-data] However, it is also possible to implement a conceptual model directly.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/structured-data] One of the earliest pioneering works in modeling information systems was done by Young and Kent (1958), who argued for "a precise and abstract way of specifying the informational and time characteristics of a data processing problem".
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/structured-data] They wanted to create "a notation that should enable the analyst to organize the problem around any piece of hardware".
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/structured-data] Their work was the first effort to create an abstract specification and invariant basis for designing different alternative implementations using different hardware components.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/structured-data] The next step in IS modeling was taken by CODASYL, an IT industry consortium formed in 1959, who essentially aimed at the same thing as Young and Kent: the development of "a proper structure for machine-independent problem definition language, at the system level of data processing".
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/structured-data] This led to the development of a specific IS information algebra.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/structured-data] In the 1960s data modeling gained more significance with the initiation of the management information system (MIS) concept.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/structured-data] According to Leondes (2002), "during that time, the information system provided the data and information for management purposes.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/structured-data] The first generation database system, called Integrated Data Store (IDS), was designed by Charles Bachman at General Electric.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/structured-data] Two famous database models, the network data model and the hierarchical data model, were proposed during this period of time".
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/structured-data] Codd worked out his theories of data arrangement, and proposed the relational model for database management based on first-order predicate logic.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/structured-data] In the 1970s entity–relationship modeling emerged as a new type of conceptual data modeling, originally formalized in 1976 by Peter Chen.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/structured-data] Entity–relationship models were being used in the first stage of information system design during the requirements analysis to describe information needs or the type of information that is to be stored in a database.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/structured-data] This technique can describe any ontology, i.e., an overview and classification of concepts and their relationships, for a certain area of interest.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/structured-data] Nijssen developed "Natural Language Information Analysis Method" (NIAM) method, and developed this in the 1980s in cooperation with Terry Halpin into Object–Role Modeling (ORM).
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/structured-data] However, it was Terry Halpin's 1989 PhD thesis that created the formal foundation on which Object–Role Modeling is based.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/structured-data] Bill Kent, in his 1978 book *Data and Reality,* compared a data model to a map of a territory, emphasizing that in the real world, "highways are not painted red, rivers don't have county lines running down the middle, and you can't see contour lines on a mountain".
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/structured-data] In contrast to other researchers who tried to create models that were mathematically clean and elegant, Kent emphasized the essential messiness of the real world, and the task of the data modeler to create order out of chaos without excessively distorting the truth.
