[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/structured-data] A database model is a specification describing how a database is structured and used.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/structured-data] Several such models have been suggested.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/structured-data] This may not strictly qualify as a data model.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/structured-data] The flat (or table) model consists of a single, two-dimensional array of data elements, where all members of a given column are assumed to be similar values, and all members of a row are assumed to be related to one another.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/structured-data] The hierarchical model is similar to the network model except that links in the hierarchical model form a tree structure, while the network model allows arbitrary graph.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/structured-data] , organizes data using two fundamental constructs, called records and sets.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/structured-data] Records (or nodes) contain fields (i.e. attributes), and sets (or edges) define one-to-many, many-to-many and many-to-one relationships between records: one owner, many members.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/structured-data] The network data model is an abstraction of the design concept used in the implementation of databases.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/structured-data] Network models emphasise interconnectedness, making them ideal for applications where relationships are crucial, like social networks or recommendation systems.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/structured-data] This structure allows for efficient querying of relationships without expensive joins.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/structured-data] is a database model based on first-order predicate logic.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/structured-data] Its core idea is to describe a database as a collection of predicates over a finite set of predicate variables, describing constraints on the possible values and combinations of values.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/structured-data] The power of the relational data model lies in its mathematical foundations and a simple user-level paradigm.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/structured-data] A method of data modeling that has been defined as "attribute free", and "fact-based".
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/structured-data] The result is a verifiably correct system, from which other common artifacts, such as ERD, UML, and semantic models may be derived.
