[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/structured-data] A data structure diagram (DSD) is a diagram and data model used to describe conceptual data models by providing graphical notations which document entities and their relationships, and the constraints that bind them.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/structured-data] The basic graphic elements of DSDs are boxes, representing entities, and arrows, representing relationships.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/structured-data] Data structure diagrams are most useful for documenting complex data entities.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/structured-data] Data structure diagrams are an extension of the entity–relationship model (ER model).
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/structured-data] In DSDs, attributes are specified inside the entity boxes rather than outside of them, while relationships are drawn as boxes composed of attributes which specify the constraints that bind entities together.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/structured-data] DSDs differ from the ER model in that the ER model focuses on the relationships between different entities, whereas DSDs focus on the relationships of the elements within an entity and enable users to fully see the links and relationships between each entity.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/structured-data] There are several styles for representing data structure diagrams, with the notable difference in the manner of defining cardinality.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/structured-data] The choices are between arrow heads, inverted arrow heads (crow's feet), or numerical representation of the cardinality.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/structured-data] An entity–relationship model (ERM), sometimes referred to as an entity–relationship diagram (ERD), could be used to represent an abstract conceptual data model (or semantic data model or physical data model) used in software engineering to represent structured data.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/structured-data] There are several notations used for ERMs.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/structured-data] Like DSD's, attributes are specified inside the entity boxes rather than outside of them, while relationships are drawn as lines, with the relationship constraints as descriptions on the line.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/structured-data] The E-R model, while robust, can become visually cumbersome when representing entities with several attributes.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/structured-data] There are several styles for representing data structure diagrams, with a notable difference in the manner of defining cardinality.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/structured-data] A data model in Geographic information systems is a mathematical construct for representing geographic objects or surfaces as data.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/structured-data] Generic data models are generalizations of conventional data models.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/structured-data] They define standardized general relation types, together with the kinds of things that may be related by such a relation type.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/structured-data] Generic data models are developed as an approach to solving some shortcomings of conventional data models.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/structured-data] For example, different modelers usually produce different conventional data models of the same domain.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/structured-data] This can lead to difficulty in bringing the models of different people together and is an obstacle for data exchange and data integration.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/structured-data] Invariably, however, this difference is attributable to different levels of abstraction in the models and differences in the kinds of facts that can be instantiated (the semantic expression capabilities of the models).
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/structured-data] The modelers need to communicate and agree on certain elements that are to be rendered more concretely, in order to make the differences less significant.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/structured-data] A semantic data model in software engineering is a technique to define the meaning of data within the context of its interrelationships with other data.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/structured-data] A semantic data model is an abstraction that defines how the stored symbols relate to the real world.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/structured-data] A semantic data model is sometimes called a conceptual data model.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/structured-data] The logical data structure of a database management system (DBMS), whether hierarchical, network, or relational, cannot totally satisfy the requirements for a conceptual definition of data because it is limited in scope and biased toward the implementation strategy employed by the DBMS.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/structured-data] Therefore, the need to define data from a conceptual view has led to the development of semantic data modeling techniques.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/structured-data] That is, techniques to define the meaning of data within the context of its interrelationships with other data.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/structured-data] The real world, in terms of resources, ideas, events, etc., are symbolically defined within physical data stores.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/structured-data] Thus, the model must be a true representation of the real world.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/structured-data] Data architecture is the design of data for use in defining the target state and the subsequent planning needed to hit the target state.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/structured-data] It is usually one of several architecture domains that form the pillars of an enterprise architecture or solution architecture.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/structured-data] A data architecture describes the data structures used by a business and/or its applications.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/structured-data] There are descriptions of data in storage and data in motion; descriptions of data stores, data groups, and data items; and mappings of those data artifacts to data qualities, applications, locations, etc.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/structured-data] Essential to realizing the target state, Data architecture describes how data is processed, stored, and utilized in a given system.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/structured-data] It provides criteria for data processing operations that make it possible to design data flows and also control the flow of data in the system.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/structured-data] Data modeling in software engineering is the process of creating a data model by applying formal data model descriptions using data modeling techniques.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/structured-data] Data modeling is a technique for defining business requirements for a database.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/structured-data] It is sometimes called *database modeling* because a data model is eventually implemented in a database.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/structured-data] The figure illustrates the way data models are developed and used today.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/structured-data] A conceptual data model is developed based on the data requirements for the application that is being developed, perhaps in the context of an activity model.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/structured-data] The data model will normally consist of entity types, attributes, relationships, integrity rules, and the definitions of those objects.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/structured-data] This is then used as the start point for interface or database design.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/structured-data] Another kind of data model describes how to organize data using a database management system or other data management technology.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/structured-data] It describes, for example, relational tables and columns or object-oriented classes and attributes.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/structured-data] Such a data model is sometimes referred to as the *physical data model*, but in the original ANSI three schema architecture, it is called "logical".
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/structured-data] In that architecture, the physical model describes the storage media (cylinders, tracks, and tablespaces).
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/structured-data] Ideally, this model is derived from the more conceptual data model described above.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/structured-data] It may differ, however, to account for constraints like processing capacity and usage patterns.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/structured-data] A different approach is to use adaptive systems such as artificial neural networks that can autonomously create implicit models of data.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/structured-data] A data structure is a way of storing data in a computer so that it can be used efficiently.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/structured-data] It is an organization of mathematical and logical concepts of data.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/structured-data] Often a carefully chosen data structure will allow the most efficient algorithm to be used.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/structured-data] The choice of the data structure often begins from the choice of an abstract data type.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/structured-data] A data model describes the structure of the data within a given domain and, by implication, the underlying structure of that domain itself.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/structured-data] This means that a data model in fact specifies a dedicated *grammar* for a dedicated artificial language for that domain.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/structured-data] A data model represents classes of entities (kinds of things) about which a company wishes to hold information, the attributes of that information, and relationships among those entities and (often implicit) relationships among those attributes.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/structured-data] The model describes the organization of the data to some extent irrespective of how data might be represented in a computer system.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/structured-data] The entities represented by a data model can be the tangible entities, but models that include such concrete entity classes tend to change over time.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/structured-data] Robust data models often identify abstractions of such entities.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/structured-data] For example, a data model might include an entity class called "Person", representing all the people who interact with an organization.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/structured-data] Such an abstract entity class is typically more appropriate than ones called "Vendor" or "Employee", which identify specific roles played by those people.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/structured-data] A data model *instance*, i.e. applying a data model *theory* to create a practical data model *instance* for some particular application.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/structured-data] For example, in the relational model, the structural part is based on a modified concept of the mathematical relation; the integrity part is expressed in first-order logic and the manipulation part is expressed using the relational algebra, tuple calculus and domain calculus.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/structured-data] A data model instance is created by applying a data model theory.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/structured-data] This is typically done to solve some business enterprise requirement.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/structured-data] Business requirements are normally captured by a semantic logical data model.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/structured-data] This is transformed into a physical data model instance from which is generated a physical database.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/structured-data] For example, a data modeler may use a data modeling tool to create an entity–relationship model of the corporate data repository of some business enterprise.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/structured-data] This model is transformed into a relational model, which in turn generates a relational database.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/structured-data] Patterns are common data modeling structures that occur in many data models.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/structured-data] A data-flow diagram (DFD) is a graphical representation of the "flow" of data through an information system.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/structured-data] It differs from the flowchart as it shows the *data* flow instead of the *control* flow of the program.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/structured-data] A data-flow diagram can also be used for the visualization of data processing (structured design).
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/structured-data] Data-flow diagrams were invented by Larry Constantine, the original developer of structured design, based on Martin and Estrin's "data-flow graph" model of computation.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/structured-data] It is common practice to draw a context-level data-flow diagram first which shows the interaction between the system and outside entities.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/structured-data] The **DFD** is designed to show how a system is divided into smaller portions and to highlight the flow of data between those parts.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/structured-data] An Information model is not a type of data model, but more or less an alternative model.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/structured-data] Within the field of software engineering, both a data model and an information model can be abstract, formal representations of entity types that include their properties, relationships and the operations that can be performed on them.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/structured-data] The entity types in the model may be kinds of real-world objects, such as devices in a network, or they may themselves be abstract, such as for the entities used in a billing system.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/structured-data] Typically, they are used to model a constrained domain that can be described by a closed set of entity types, properties, relationships and operations.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/structured-data] According to Lee (1999) an information model is a representation of concepts, relationships, constraints, rules, and operations to specify data semantics for a chosen domain of discourse.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/structured-data] It can provide sharable, stable, and organized structure of information requirements for the domain context.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/structured-data] More in general the term *information model* is used for models of individual things, such as facilities, buildings, process plants, etc.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/structured-data] In those cases the concept is specialised to Facility Information Model, Building Information Model, Plant Information Model, etc.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/structured-data] Such an information model is an integration of a model of the facility with the data and documents about the facility.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/structured-data] An information model provides formalism to the description of a problem domain without constraining how that description is mapped to an actual implementation in software.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/structured-data] There may be many mappings of the information model.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/structured-data] Such mappings are called data models, irrespective of whether they are object models (e.g. using UML), entity–relationship models or XML schemas.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/structured-data] An object model in computer science is a collection of objects or classes through which a program can examine and manipulate some specific parts of its world.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/structured-data] In other words, the object-oriented interface to some service or system.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/structured-data] Such an interface is said to be the *object model of* the represented service or system.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/structured-data] For example, the Document Object Model (DOM) [1] is a collection of objects that represent a page in a web browser, used by script programs to examine and dynamically change the page.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/structured-data] There is a Microsoft Excel object model for controlling Microsoft Excel from another program, and the ASCOM Telescope Driver is an object model for controlling an astronomical telescope.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/structured-data] In computing the term *object model* has a distinct second meaning of the general properties of objects in a specific computer programming language, technology, notation or methodology that uses them.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/structured-data] For example, the *Java object model*, the *COM object model*, or *the object model of OMT*.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/structured-data] Such object models are usually defined using concepts such as class, message, inheritance, polymorphism, and encapsulation.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/structured-data] There is an extensive literature on formalized object models as a subset of the formal semantics of programming languages.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/structured-data] Object–Role Modeling (ORM) is a method for conceptual modeling, and can be used as a tool for information and rules analysis.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/structured-data] Object–Role Modeling is a fact-oriented method for performing systems analysis at the conceptual level.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/structured-data] The quality of a database application depends critically on its design.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/structured-data] To help ensure correctness, clarity, adaptability and productivity, information systems are best specified first at the conceptual level, using concepts and language that people can readily understand.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/structured-data] The conceptual design may include data, process and behavioral perspectives, and the actual DBMS used to implement the design might be based on one of many logical data models (relational, hierarchic, network, object-oriented, etc.).
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/structured-data] The Unified Modeling Language (UML) is a standardized general-purpose modeling language in the field of software engineering.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/structured-data] It is a graphical language for visualizing, specifying, constructing, and documenting the artifacts of a software-intensive system.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/structured-data] UML offers a mix of functional models, data models, and database models.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/template-c] In plain terms, a templated class or function would be the equivalent of (before "compiling") copying and pasting the templated block of code where it is used, and then replacing the template parameter with the actual one.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/template-c] For this reason, classes employing templated methods place the implementation in the headers (*.h files) as no symbol could be compiled without knowing the type beforehand.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/template-c] The C++ Standard Library provides many useful functions within a framework of connected templates.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/template-c] Major inspirations for C++ templates were the parameterized modules provided by the language CLU and the generics provided by Ada.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/template-c] There are three kinds of templates: *function templates*, *class templates* and, since C++14, *variable templates*.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/template-c] Since C++11, templates may be either variadic or non-variadic; in earlier versions of C++ they are always non-variadic.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/template-c] A *function template* behaves like a function except that the template can accept arguments of various types, enabling type-generic behavior (see example).
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/template-c] In other words, a function template represents a family of functions.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/template-c] Both expressions have the same meaning and behave in exactly the same way.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/template-c] The latter form was introduced to avoid confusion, since a type parameter need not be a class until C++20.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/template-c] For example, the C++ Standard Library contains the function template `max(x, y)` which returns the larger of `x` and `y`.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/template-c] This single function definition works with many data types.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/template-c] Specifically, it works with all data types for which **<** (the less-than operator) is defined and returns a value with a type convertible to `bool`.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/template-c] The usage of a function template saves space in the source code file in addition to limiting changes to one function description and making the code easier to read.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/template-c] An instantiated function template usually produces the same object code, though, compared to writing separate functions for all the different data types used in a specific program.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/template-c] For example, if a program uses both an `int` and a `double` version of the `max()` function template above, the compiler will create an object code version of `max()` that operates on `int` arguments and another object code version that operates on `double` arguments.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/template-c] The compiler output will be identical to what would have been produced if the source code had contained two separate non-templated versions of `max()`, one written to handle `int` and one written to handle `double`.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/template-c] In the first two cases, the template argument `T` is automatically deduced by the compiler to be `int` and `double`, respectively.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/template-c] In the third case automatic deduction of `max(3, 7.0)` would fail because the type of the parameters must in general match the template arguments exactly.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/template-c] Therefore, we explicitly instantiate the `double` version with `max<double>()`.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/template-c] This function template can be instantiated with any copy-constructible type for which the expression `y < x` is valid.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/template-c] For user-defined types, this implies that the less-than operator (`<`) must be overloaded in the type.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/template-c] Since C++20, using `auto` or `concept auto` in any of the parameters of a function declaration, that declaration becomes an *abbreviated function template* declaration.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/template-c] A class template provides a specification for generating classes based on parameters.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/template-c] Class templates are generally used to implement containers.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/template-c] A class template is instantiated by passing a given set of types to it as template arguments.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/template-c] The C++ Standard Library contains many class templates, in particular the containers adapted from the Standard Template Library, such as `vector`.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/template-c] Although templating on types, as in the examples above, is the most common form of templating in C++, it is also possible to template on values.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/template-c] can be instantiated with a specific `int`.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/template-c] As a real-world example, the standard library fixed-size array type `std::array` is templated on both a type (representing the type of object that the array holds) and a number which is of type `std::size_t` (representing the number of elements the array holds).
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/template-c] When a function or class is instantiated from a template, a specialization of that template is created by the compiler for the set of arguments used, and the specialization is referred to as being a generated specialization.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/template-c] Sometimes, the programmer may decide to implement a special version of a function (or class) for a given set of template type arguments which is called an explicit specialization.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/template-c] In this way certain template types can have a specialized implementation that is optimized for the type or a more meaningful implementation than the generic implementation.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/template-c] Explicit specialization is used when the behavior of a function or class for particular choices of the template parameters must deviate from the generic behavior: that is, from the code generated by the main template, or templates.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/template-c] C++11 introduced variadic templates, which can take a variable number of arguments in a manner somewhat similar to variadic functions such as `std::printf`.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/template-c] Because only C-style variadic parameters are supported in C++, the only way to get type-safe variadic functions (like in Java) is through variadic templates.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/template-c] C++11 introduced template aliases, which act like parameterized typedefs.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/template-c] The following code shows renaming `std::map` to `TreeMap` and `std::unordered_map` to `HashMap`, as well as creating an alias `StringHashMap` for `std::unordered_map<K, std::string>`.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/template-c] This allows, for example, `StringHashMap<int>` to be used as shorthand for `std::unordered_map<int, std::string>`.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/template-c] Since C++20, templates can be constrained similarly to generics wildcards in Java or C# and Rust `where` clauses.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/template-c] This is done using concepts, which represent a set of boolean predicates evaluated at compile time.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/template-c] For example, this code uses `std::derived_from<Derived, Based>` as an upper inheritance bound.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/template-c] A class satisfies this concept if it inherits from `Player`, and classes that do not cannot be used as the template parameter in `processListOfPlayers()`.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/template-c] Concepts can be used to implement a form of type-safe variadic parameters.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/template-c] Furthermore, to constrain these to any specific type, the `std::same_as<T, U>` and `std::convertible_to<T, U>` concepts may be used.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/template-c] For instance, the Java signatures `void foo(int... args);` and `void bar(String... args);` could be written as `void foo(same_as<int> auto... args);` and `void bar(convertible_to<string> auto... args);` respectively.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/template-c] In C++03, "exported templates" were added to C++.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/template-c] These were later removed in C++11, due to very few compilers actually supporting the feature.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/template-c] The only compiler known to support exported templates was Comeau C/C++.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/template-c] An "exported template" is essentially a class template whose static data members and non-inline methods are exported.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/template-c] It must be marked by the keyword `export`.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/template-c] What distinguishes an "exported template" is the fact that it does not need to be defined in a translation unit that uses the template.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/template-c] With the introduction of modules in C++20, the keyword `export` was re-added to C++.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/template-c] The compilation speed benefits intended to be offered by exported templates are offered by modules anyway, making the feature essentially obsolete and superseded by modules.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/template-c] Initially, the concept of templates was not included in some languages, such as Java and C# 1.0.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/template-c] Java's adoption of generics mimics the behavior of templates, but is technically different.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/template-c] C# added generics (parameterized types) in .NET 2.0.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/template-c] The generics in Ada predate C++ templates.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/template-c] Although C++ templates, Java generics, and .NET generics are often considered similar, generics only mimic the basic behavior of C++ templates.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/template-c] In C++ templates, compile-time cases were historically performed by pattern matching over the template arguments.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/template-c] For example, the template base class in the Factorial example below is implemented by matching 0 rather than with an inequality test, which was previously unavailable.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/template-c] However, the arrival in C++11 of standard library features such as `std::conditional` has provided another, more flexible way to handle conditional template instantiation.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/template-c] With these definitions, one can compute, say 6! at compile time using the expression `Factorial<6>::value`.
[src:spdlog-cpp-lib/template-c] Because of this, template meta-programming is now mostly used to do operations on types.
